{{About||the entire series of The Secret Policeman's Ball shows|The Secret Policeman's Ball|the DVD box set of The Secret Policeman's Ball shows|The Secret Policeman's Balls (DVD box set)}}

'''''The Secret Policeman's Ball''''' was the third of the [[benefit concert|benefit shows]] staged by [[Amnesty International]] to raise funds for its research and campaign work in the [[human rights]] field.  In later years, other Amnesty benefit shows also bore the ''Secret Policeman's'' title. They are informally referred to as ''[[The Secret Policeman's Balls]]''.

''The Secret Policeman's Ball'' took place over four consecutive nights in [[London]] on 27–30 June 1979. It was a successor to the 1976 show ''[[A Poke In The Eye (With A Sharp Stick)]]'' (the film of which was titled ''[[Pleasure At Her Majesty's]]'') and the 1977 show ''The Mermaid Frolics''.

The show was directed by [[Monty Python]] alumnus [[John Cleese]] and producers [[Martin Lewis (humorist)|Martin Lewis]] and Peter Walker.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywood.com/movie/The_Secret_Policemans_Ball/226036/|title=Movie News, Theaters, Reviews, Trailers & Photos - Hollywood.com|work=Hollywood.com}}</ref> It subsequently yielded a one-hour TV special, a full-length film, and two record albums (one each of comedy and music performances).

One of the sketches in the show was [[Peter Cook]]'s nine-minute parody of the biased judge's instructions to the jury in the recently concluded [[Thorpe affair|Jeremy Thorpe trial]], titled "Entirely a Matter for You".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://asketchofthepast.com/2014/12/06/in-his-own-time-the-trials-of-jeremy-thorpe/|title=In His Own Time: The Trials Of Jeremy Thorpe - A Sketch Of The Past|date=6 December 2014|publisher=|accessdate=4 June 2018}}</ref> The sketch was, according to Freeman and Penrose, "actually not that different from the original".<ref>{{cite book|last1= Freeman|first1= Simon|last2= Penrose|first2= Barrie |author-link2=Barrie Penrose |title= Rinkagate: The Rise and Fall of Jeremy Thorpe|location= London|publisher= Bloomsbury Publications|year= 1997|isbn= 0-7475-3339-3|page=365}}</ref> It is considered to be one of the finest works of Cook's career. Cook and show producer [[Martin Lewis (humorist)|Martin Lewis]] brought out an album on [[Virgin Records]] entitled ''Here Comes the Judge: Live'' of the live performance together with three studio tracks that further lampooned the Thorpe trial.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.phespirit.info/pictures/heroes/p008_info.htm |title=Peter Cook |publisher=Phespirit.info |accessdate=25 July 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100113163211/http://www.phespirit.info/pictures/heroes/p008_info.htm |archivedate=13 January 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> 

Musicians-turned-activists such as [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], [[Peter Gabriel]], [[Bob Geldof]] and [[Bono]] have attributed their participation in [[human rights]] issues to their exposure to Amnesty via ''The Secret Policeman's Ball'' show. Bono told ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine in 1986, “I saw ''The Secret Policeman’s Ball'' and it became a part of me. It sowed a seed..."

